gostow is an independent reimplementation of GNU Stow, written in Go. It shares
no source code with GNU Stow, which is written in Perl and licensed under the
GNU General Public License, version 3 or later.

    GNU Stow — https://www.gnu.org/software/stow/
    Copyright (c) Bob Glickstein, Adam Spiers, and contributors.

gostow reproduces GNU Stow's *behaviour*: its option names and their parsing,
its exit codes, its diagnostic messages, and the symlink farm it builds. Those
are facts about an interface, and reimplementing them is what this project is.

Two pieces of GNU Stow's text are reproduced literally, because reproducing them
is the behaviour:

  * The built-in ignore list — the patterns in Stow.pm's __DATA__ section
    (RCS, CVS, .git, backup files, and so on), copied into stow/ignore.go. A
    file GNU Stow declines to stow must be a file gostow declines to stow; the
    patterns *are* the specification. They are short, functional regular
    expressions with no expressive latitude.

  * Individual error and conflict messages, which scripts and users read, and
    which must therefore match byte for byte.

GNU Stow's --help text is NOT reproduced. gostow's help is written in gostow's
own words, points at gostow's own issue tracker, and links GNU Stow's manual as
the authority on what the shared options mean. See docs/SPEC.md §4.5.

Where an option's meaning needs more than a line, GNU Stow's manual describes
gostow exactly, and is the better document:

    https://www.gnu.org/software/stow/manual/

GNU Stow 2.4.1 is also gostow's test oracle: the differential suite builds the
real Perl program from its released tarball and compares gostow against it. That
build happens on a developer's or CI machine and is never redistributed as part
of gostow. See test/install-stow-oracle.sh.
